FeedPackage.Description:
Data mapper ========= Contains a data mapper layer built as an extension to ADO.NET. i.e. the layer do not hide ADO.NET but extends it making it trivial to do CRUD operations and map DB records to domain entities
Performant networking ================ Contains a performant networking layer removed the need to do the raw IO operations yourself.
Use our built in HTTP library for interoperability or our built in protocol MicroMsg to easily send/receive .NET objects over the network.
IoC support ======== Many parts of the library have built in IoC support. You can for instance use attributes to automatically register your classes in the container (without a RegisterType line for every class)
Read more at the project homepage.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
Added IBackgroundJobAsync to enable TPL in background jobs.
Pulled out the core features in the IEntityMapper to IEntityMapperBase to allow mappings when no CRUD operations is desired (i.e. only used for SELECTs).
FeedPackage.Summary:
Allows you to write your applications faster and more cleanly.
* Performant networking lib * ADO.NET data mapper * IoC support for long running tasks/jobs * Easier IoC registrations

Data mapper ========= Contains a data mapper layer built as an extension to ADO.NET. i.e. the layer do not hide ADO.NET but extends it making it trivial to do CRUD operations and map DB records to domain entities
Performant networking ================ Contains a performant networking layer removed the need to do the raw IO operations yourself.
Use our built in HTTP library for interoperability or our built in protocol MicroMsg to easily send/receive .NET objects over the network.
IoC support ======== Many parts of the library have built in IoC support. You can for instance use attributes to automatically register your classes in the container (without a RegisterType line for every class)
Read more at the project homepage.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: Added fluent mappings for the data mapper.
FeedPackage.Summary:
Allows you to write your applications faster and more cleanly.
* Fast network lib * ADO.NET data mapper * IoC support for long running tasks/jobs * Easier IoC registrations * DI in WinServices

FeedPackage.Description:
Command/Query (CQS) library which enables to you use dependency injection in your Command/Query handlers.
The CQS objects can be executed locally within the same process or through a client/server architecture.
You can also scale the execution by using routing CQS objects or divide so that one server handles events, another queries etc.
Support for:
* Commands * Queries * Request/Reply * Application events

FeedPackage.Description:
Enables MSBuild integration for the SharpLinter tool written by James Treworgy
The package includes the most recent SharpLinter binaries and JSHint 2.5.6 and provides an MSBuild target for running SharpLinter as a part of the build process.
In addition, the package enforces Visual Studio-compatible formatting for JSHint warning so that they are correctly shown in the Errors tab in Visual Studio.
This is a first release with quite a limited functionality. Please refer to the Release Notes for known limitations.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
IMPORTANT ------------- 1) Requires the SolutionDir MSBuild property to be defined so once this package has been added to a project, the project can no longer be built with MSBuild without the enclosing solution unless you provide the correct value of the SolutionDir property in command line arguments.
2) It is assumed that the SharpLinter configuration file is named "sharplinter.conf" and is located in the project root folder. A boilerplate configuration file will be added to the project upon installing the NuGet package. The SharpLinter configuration file location can be overridden by defining the "SharpLinterConfigFile" MSBuild property in the Visual Studio project file.
KNOWN LIMITATIONS ------------------------ 1) JSHint warnings are always reported as warnings in Visual Studio but an error will be reported if at least one warning was found by JSHint. There currently is no configuration option to change that. 2) Tested only with Visual Studio 2012
FeedPackage.Title: sharplinter-msbuild

FeedPackage.Description:
Enables MSBuild integration for the SharpLinter tool written by James Treworgy
The package includes the most recent SharpLinter binaries and JSHint 2.5.6 and provides an MSBuild target for running SharpLinter as a part of the build process.
In addition, the package enforces Visual Studio-compatible formatting for JSHint warning so that they are correctly shown in the Errors tab in Visual Studio.
This is a first release with quite a limited functionality. Please refer to the Release Notes for known limitations.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
VERSION HISTORY ------------------------
0.2.1:
1) Updated sharplinter.conf with a complete set of supported JSHint options 2) Removed "alert", "confirm" and "jQuery" from known global variables as these are made known to JSHint via specialized options.
0.2.0:
Initial public release with basic functions working
IMPORTANT ------------------------ 1) Requires the SolutionDir MSBuild property to be defined so once this package has been added to a project, the project can no longer be built with MSBuild without the enclosing solution unless you provide the correct value of the SolutionDir property in command line arguments.
2) It is assumed that the SharpLinter configuration file is named "sharplinter.conf" and is located in the project root folder. A boilerplate configuration file will be added to the project upon installing the NuGet package. The SharpLinter configuration file location can be overridden by defining the "SharpLinterConfigFile" MSBuild property in the Visual Studio project file.
KNOWN LIMITATIONS ------------------------ 1) JSHint warnings are always reported as warnings in Visual Studio but an error will be reported if at least one warning was found by JSHint. There currently is no configuration option to change that. 2) Tested only with Visual Studio 2012
